<dl id="n53097aa"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n53" href="#n53097aa">N53 (VI.B.46)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n53all.htm#n53097aa"> 97(aa)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> veerey / lights <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n53097aa"><li>FW 344.23 </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/lexmd.htm#n53097aa">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/md/l39md.htm#n53097aa">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n53097aa">MS BL 47480-82v</ms> </li><li>JJA 55:156 <a name="mdd5" href="../../FF/fdra/mda.htm#mdd5">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/md/mdd5.htm#n53097aa">Draft: II.3&sect;4.5</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Now one may say at once that Percy had all the makings in him of the true artist. Having decided to stage his performance, he had no intention of letting it fail through lack of attention to detail. Life in the front trenches is not at any time an enlivening proceeding; the days drag wearily by, the nights are full of noises and <mark>Verey lights</mark>&mdash;and this particular part of the line was no exception to the general rule. <small> H.C. McNeile (&ldquo;Sapper&rdquo;) <a name="SJW" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#SJW"><cite title="source">John Walters</cite></a> (1927) The Man-Trap, 113</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: [Army slang] Very light: a flare discharged from a brass pistol. [Varied light.] </mm> </dd></dl>
